==========================================================================
1. OPENSHIFT CLUSTER ACCESS
==========================================================================

Console URL:       {{ cluster_console_url }}
API Endpoint:      {{ cluster_api_url }}
Identity Provider: {{ htpasswd_identity_provider_name }}
Namespace:         {{ partner_namespace }}

User credentials (use the "{{ htpasswd_identity_provider_name }}" login option):

{% for user in partner_users_with_pw %}
  Username: {{ user.username }}
  Password: {{ user.password }}
  Email:    {{ user.email }}

{% endfor %}

What you can do:
  - Full admin rights inside the {{ partner_namespace }} namespace
  - Browse OperatorHub and install namespace-scoped operators
    (operators that support OwnNamespace or SingleNamespace mode)
  - Access the RHOAI dashboard for your Data Science Project
  - Use the OpenShift CLI: oc login {{ cluster_api_url }}

What you cannot do:
  - Install cluster-wide operators (RHOAI, GitOps, Pipelines, MTV, etc.)
    These are already installed cluster-wide and shared across partners.
  - Modify other namespaces or cluster-level resources

{% if enable_aap_controller %}
==========================================================================
2. ANSIBLE AUTOMATION PLATFORM (CONTROLLER)
==========================================================================

Controller URL:    {{ aap_controller_url }}
Organization:      {{ partner_name }}
Team:              {{ partner_name }} Admins

User credentials (these are SEPARATE from your OpenShift credentials):

{% for user in aap_users_with_pw %}
  Username: {{ user.username }}
  Password: {{ user.aap_password }}

{% endfor %}

Pre-configured resources in your organization:
  - Credential: "{{ partner_name }} OpenShift ({{ partner_namespace }} namespace)"
    Pre-scoped to your namespace via a ServiceAccount token. Use this in
    your job templates to interact with OpenShift.
  - Inventory: "{{ partner_name }} Lab" (empty starter)

You have org-admin rights, so you can create your own projects, job
templates, additional credentials, inventories, and execution environments
within your organization.

{% endif %}
{% if enable_aap_eda %}
==========================================================================
3. EVENT-DRIVEN ANSIBLE (EDA)
==========================================================================

EDA URL:           {{ aap_eda_url }}

User credentials (SEPARATE from both OpenShift and AAP Controller creds):

{% for user in eda_users_with_pw %}
  Username: {{ user.username }}
  Password: {{ user.eda_password }}

{% endfor %}

Note: This version of EDA does not have organizational scoping. Anything
you create in EDA (Decision Environments, Rulebook Activations, etc.) is
visible to other EDA users on the cluster. Be mindful of naming and don't
include secrets in rulebook source.

You have Contributor role, which lets you:
  - Create and run Decision Environments and Rulebook Activations
  - Create Event Streams and Projects
  - View other users' resources (no isolation in this version)

You cannot manage other EDA users.

{% endif %}
